Merge pull request #538 from opt9/fix_dup

Fix duplicate test id

GlassFish version numbers are not IP addresses

In case of GlassFish servers, the `x-powered-by` header contains the
version number, which happens to contain four single-digit parts,
resulting in the following lines being printed during a scan.

    + Retrieved x-powered-by header: Servlet/3.0 JSP/2.2 (Oracle
      GlassFish Server 3.1.2.2 Java/Oracle Corporation/1.7)
    + IP address found in the 'x-powered-by' header.
      The IP is "3.1.2.2".

This patch ignores `x-powered-by` headers that contain a GlassFish
server banner when looking for IP addresses.

Add a new plugin for detection CORS Origin header reflection

The issue seems to be that some applications or servers will simply
reflected a given Origin header back in the Access-Control-Allow-Origin
response, leading to a CORS bypass. This also includes a case where
the reflected header includes a wildcard by fuzzy matching the header.

The issue is discussed further in:
http://blog.portswigger.net/2016/10/exploiting-cors-misconfigurations-for.html

used. For example, if you have USERAGENT=aaa=bbb, the useragent should be set
to aaa=bbb and only the first `=` should be used for the split.

WebSEAL version numbers are not IP addresses

In case of [WebSEAL](https://stackoverflow.com/tags/webseal/info) servers, the `Server` header contains the version number, which happens to contain four single-digit parts, resulting in the followin lines being printed during a scan.

    + Server: WebSEAL/8.0.1.3
    + IP address found in the 'server' header. The IP is "8.0.1.3".

This patch ignores `Server` headers that start with `WebSEAL/` when looking for IP addresses.

Merge pull request #72 from peaceful/master

Don't use an unsanitized user-defined URL as a regular expression.

User-defined URLs should not be used as regular expressions without being sanitized - which is ironically the kind of thing Nikto is looking for in the first place.  :-)  Without this change, a URL like '/[blah.txt' would cause a crash due to the URL itself being an invalid regular expression pattern.  Tyler Farr assisted with finding this problem and devising a fix.
